{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17486609","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17486609"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T02:38:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"143"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/143"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.18,0.04,0.22,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77166"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"143","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/143"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"143"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62673"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"205"},{"type":"tags","id":"1787"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"11009"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"964"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1295"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3565"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77166"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of progressive breathlessness, worse with exertion and lying flat. She denies cough. She has an inherited muscular disorder requiring wheelchair use. She has gastro-oesophageal reflux disease but no other medical conditions. Her only medication is pantoprazole.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 120/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 19/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is symmetrically reduced chest expansion. The percussion note is resonant throughout. Air entry is poor bilaterally with normal breath sounds. She has severe kyphoscoliosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary function testing is arranged to assess Forced Expiratory Volume in 1 second (FEV1), Forced Vital Capacity (FVC), Total Lung Capacity (TLC) and Diffusing Capacity of carbon monoxide (DLco).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following patterns is most likely to be found on pulmonary function testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["FEV1/FVC \u003E80% predicted, increased TLC, reduced DLco","FEV1/FVC \u003C80% predicted, reduced TLC, normal DLco","FEV1/FVC \u003C80% predicted, increased TLC, normal DLco","FEV1/FVC \u003E80% predicted, reduced TLC, reduced DLco","FEV1/FVC \u003E80% predicted, reduced TLC, normal DLco"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of restrictive lung disease due to two extra-thoracic causes: neuromuscular disease and kyphoscoliosis. The key clinical features supporting this are orthopnoea, reduced chest expansion, and poor air entry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC \u0026gt;80% predicted, reduced TLC, normal DLco\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic pattern seen in extra-thoracic restriction. The FEV1/FVC ratio remains normal or high because both values are reduced proportionally. TLC is reduced due to mechanical limitation of chest wall expansion. DLco remains normal because the underlying lung parenchyma is unaffected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC \u0026gt;80% predicted, reduced TLC, reduced DLco\u003C/strong\u003E is the pattern seen in intrinsic lung diseases such as pulmonary fibrosis, which would present differently with fine crackles and different clinical features.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC \u0026lt;80% predicted, increased TLC, normal DLco\u003C/strong\u003E is the pattern seen in obstructive lung disease such as asthma or COPD, which this patient does not have clinical features of.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC \u0026lt;80% predicted, reduced TLC, normal DLco\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest a mixed obstructive-restrictive pattern, which is not consistent with this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFEV1/FVC \u0026gt;80% predicted, increased TLC, reduced DLco\u003C/strong\u003E would be an unusual combination not typically seen in any common respiratory condition. Increased TLC suggests hyperinflation, which would not occur with a reduced DLco.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In restrictive lung disease, FEV1/FVC ratio is preserved (\u003E80%) while TLC is reduced","Extra-thoracic causes of restriction (like neuromuscular disease and kyphoscoliosis) typically have normal diffusion capacity","Clinical features of restrictive lung disease include reduced chest expansion and orthopnoea"],"references":["Ponce MC, Sharma S. Pulmonary Function Tests. In: StatPearls [online]. 2020. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482339/","Ward NS, Hill NS. Pulmonary function testing in neuromuscular disease. Clin Chest Med. 2001 Dec;22(4):769-81. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11787664/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62673"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"143"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62673"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T10:58:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T10:58:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","i